            h2(id='signals') Basics: What Are Signals
            br

            p In Linux, processes communicate through a mechanism called <b>signals</b>. A signal is a message sent to a process by the operating system or another process to notify it of an event or request an action.
            
            p <strong>Common Signals Used for Termination:</strong>
            <ul>
                <li><b>SIGTERM (15)</b> ‚Äî <i>"Graceful"</i> termination (default).</li>
                <li><b>SIGKILL (9)</b> ‚Äî Forceful termination (cannot be intercepted or ignored)</li>
                <li><b>SIGHUP (1)</b> ‚Äî Reload configuration or <i>"hang up"</i> signal.</li>
                <li><b>SIGINT (2)</b> ‚Äî Interrupt signal (same as pressing <kbd>Ctrl+C</kbd> in a terminal).</li>
            </ul>

            p (To see the complete list of all available signals, open a Linux terminal and run the command <code>kill -l</code>)
            
            p üëâ <b>Rule of thumb</b>: always start with <b>SIGTERM</b> and use <b>SIGKILL</b> only as a last resort.
  

