            h2(id='kill') The <code>kill</code> Command: Your Primary Tool
            br

            <p><strong>Basic Syntax:</strong></p>

            pre(class="bg-light")
                code.
                    kill [-s sigspec | -n signum | -sigspec] pid

            p Where:
            <ul>
                <li><b>sigspec</b> ‚Äî signal name (e.g., TERM, KILL, HUP)</li>
                <li><b>signum</b> ‚Äî signal number (e.g., 15, 9, 1)</li>
                <li><b>pid</b> ‚Äî process ID</li>
            </ul>

            br
            br

            p <strong>Main Principles:</strong>
            <ul>
                <li>Use <b>SIGTERM</b> by default.</li>
                <li>Give processes time to shut down gracefully.</li>
                <li>Use <b>SIGKILL</b> only if the process doesn‚Äôt respond.</li>
                <li>Inspect the process before killing it (<code>ps</code>, <code>top</code>, <code>htop</code>).</li>
                <li>For system services, prefer <code>systemctl stop</code> over <code>kill</code>.</li>
            </ul>
            
            br
            br

            h4 <strong>Practical Examples</strong>

            p <strong>Graceful Termination (Recommended)</strong>
            pre(class="bg-light")
                code.
                    > kill 1234
                    > kill -TERM 1234
                    > kill -s TERM 1234
                    > kill -n 15 1234


            br


            p <strong>Forceful Termination (Last Resort)</strong>
            pre(class="bg-light")
                code.
                    > kill -9 1234
                    > kill -KILL 1234
                    > kill -s KILL 1234
                    > kill -n 9 1234

            br

            p <strong>Reload Configuration</strong>
            pre(class="bg-light")
                code.
                    > kill -HUP 1234
                    > kill -s HUP 1234
                    > kill -n 1 1234

